Dataset: stories.zip Download stories.zip

The dataset has several small stories in text file. Consider each story as separate document.

Term - Frequency Inverse Document Frequency

1) Remove Stopwords (1 Mark)

2) Remove the punctuations. the special characters and convert the text to lower case. (2 Mark)

3) create bigrams for the entire dataset and list down 10 most frequent bigrams. ( 2 Marks )

4) You have to implement TF-IDF the Algorithm from scratch. ( 4 Mark )

5) Use the above-implemented algorithm and the values to calculate TF-IDF (using TF IDF formula) on the preprocessed data for unigrams and list down the top 10 words which have the highest TF-IDF Value. (2 Marks)

Refer to the following link to create POS labeled data: https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/part-speech-tagging-stop-words-using-nltk-python/

Perform Part of Speech Tagging using the Viterbi Algorithm,

6) Label the cleaned Tf-IDF dataset ( obtained after performing step 1 and step 2 ) ( 2 Mark )

7) Split the Train and the Test Dataset (1 Mark)

8) Implement the Viterbi Algorithm ( you can use Library) to get the Part of Speech Tagging. ( 3 Marks)

9) Calculate the Accuracy and F1 score. ( Number of Predicted Correct Tag in the test set / Total number of Data points in the test set) (2 Marks)

Topic Modelling

Use cleaned Tf-IDF dataset ( obtained after performing step 1 and step 2 )

10) Using the LDA algorithm create the Topics (10) for the Corpus (3 Marks)

11) List down the 10 words in each of the Topics Extracted. (2 Marks)

Note: You may ignore if you find the words in the topic are not highly related.

['                                FOR CHILDREN:\n\n                                   Sly Fox\n\n    Mr. Rabbit sat on his front porch rocking, eating a great big carrot, \nand looking.\n\n    "Looks like Sly Fox coming down the road," he said to himself, walking \nto the end of the porch. Shading his eyes with his paws, he exclaimed, "It \nis Sly Fox." \n\n    "Good morning Mr. Rabbit," cried Sly Fox, as he walked across the yard. \n"Good morning," replied Mr. Rabbit, a slight frown on his face. \n\n    "Well," said Sly Fox, "as I haven\'t seen you in so long a time, thought \nI would stop and chat a while." \n\n    Mr. Rabbit could not be rude in his own home, even to an enemy, so he \noffered Sly Fox a seat on the porch. \n\n    "Take a chair," he said politely. \tBut Sly Fox did not stay long, and as \nhe was leaving, he asked: "Mr. Rabbit, my mother is having a good dinner \ntonight. Won\'t you, Mrs. Rabbit, and your three little rabs come to dinner \nwith me?" \n\n    Oh, thought Mr. Rabbit, he knows about my little rabs and wants to take \nus off to eat us. He pretended to be disappointed as he replied: "Sorry, Sly \nFox, we have an engagement for today, but if you want us we can come \ntomorrow." \n\n    At this Sly Fox chuckled inwardly, and readily agreed to come for them \nthe next day. Wishing Mr. Rabbit "Good day", he trotted on down the road \ntoward his home. \n\n    As soon as he was out of sight, Mr. Rabbit ran into his house and called \nMrs. Rabbit. "Get all our things together," he said, "and put rubber boots \non our little rabs. We have to move quickly to the Piney Woods across the \nbrook. Old Sly Fox has found our home and will destroy us." \n\n    In no time at all the Rabbit family had moved, and the little rabs were \ndelighted with their new home. A woodland of towering pines it was, the \nground covered with pine needles which made a soft carpeting. The wind made \nmusic in the pine trees, birds sang, and the fragrance of flowers filled the \nair. They found a huge hollow tree where Mr. Rabbit burrowed deep and made \nthem a cozy home. Squirrels had left nuts hidden around in the old tree. \nOwls hooted throughout the night, crickets chirped merrily. \n\n    Next morning old Sly Fox knocked on the door where he had left Mr. \nRabbit. Mrs. Hedgehog answered the door. "Good morning, Mrs. Hedgehog. Is \nMr. Rabbit in?" inquired Sly Fox with a wicked grin and a cunning look in \nhis eyes. \n\n    "No," replied Mrs. Eedgehog, none too cordially. "The Rabbit family \nmoved to parts unknown right after you left yesterday." \n\n    "Ah," exclaimed old Sly Fox, "Mr. Rabbit and family were going to have \ndinner with me. My mother has planned a real feast. Why don\'t you come and \nenjoy it with us?" \n\n    "Oh," replied Mrs. Hedgehog, smacking her lips and thinking of all the \ngoodies, "I have just moved in and there is so much to do! Why not let it go \nuntil tomorrow?" \n\n    "Do you like nice young grasshoppers?" asked Sly Fox softly. \n\n    "Do I? Nothing so good as tender young grasshoppers," answered Mrs. \nHedgehog, fairly dribbling at the mouth at the thought of such a dainty. \n\n    "Well," said Sly Fox, "we pass a field where there are any number of \nthem. Come get in this sack, and when I stop in the field we will open the \nsack and rake in all of them we want. Mother will bake them with apples and \nthey will be deilicious!" This was too much for greedy Mrs. Hedgehog to \nresist, so in the sack she went. Sly Fox with a grin grabbed the sack, threw \nit over his shoulder and trotted toward home. \tAfter going a long way, Mrs. \nHedgehog became suspicious and cried, "How long before we reach that field \nof grasshoppers?" \n\n    "Why, you silly, greedy hedgehog, there is no field of grasshoppers for \nyou. I am going to eat you for my dinner. It\'s you with apple dumplings that \nmy mother will bake." \n\n    Every hair on Mrs. Hedgehog\'s head stood on end with fright. Oh, how \nfoolish she had been! Her greed had trapped her. If only she had stayed home \nand straightened her house and cooked her own dinner, she would not have \nbeen in this sack to be eaten by Sly Fox. Greediness never pays, she thought \nto herself. \n\n    Sly Fox became tired, and as a slight rain had begun to fall, he looked \nfor a dry place to sit down. Throwing the sack to the ground and chuckling \nat the thought of sitting on Mrs. Hedgehog, he dropped heavily upon the \nsack. \n\n    "Wow, Wow!" he cried, jumping quickly up, for Mrs. Hedgehog shot her \nsharp quills into him with all her might. \n\n    Sly Fox ran to and fro trying to pull out the quills, but they had gone \ntoo deep. Home he ran, screaming to his mother. Old Mother Fox threw him \nover a log and began pulling out the quills, at the same time calling to a \nneighbor fox to bring some honey to put on the places where the quills had \nbeen. \n\n    Mrs. Hedgehog crawled out of the bag and began walking slowly toward \nhome. She thought to herself that never again would she be so greedy and \nallow herself to be fooled by Sly Fox or any one else. \n\n    Meanwhile, Mr. Rabbit and family were living happily in Piney Woods. The \nlittle rabs played on the crystal clear brook that ran through the woods, \nwading, sailing little leaf boats, and trying to catch the silvery minnows \ndarting here and there. \n\n    Late one evening Papa and Mama Rabbit were sitting before the cozy fire \ntalking. Papa Rabbit had on his house robe and bedroom slippers, reading the \nnewspaper. Every now and then he looked over his spectacles lovingly at \ndainty little Mama Rabbit, dressed in a flowered housecoat and red slippers \nand knitting little socks for the little rabs. \n\n    "Sniff! Sniff! Sniff!" came suddenly to their ears. \n\n    "Sly Fox!" whispered Papa Rabbit, his face now full of concern and \nalarm. \n\n    "Yes," agreed Mama Rabbit, her voice trembling with fright. \n\n    "Go cover the little rabs with straw and tell them to be very, very \nquiet," instructed Papa Rabbit. \n\n    Mrs. Rabbit quickly covered the little rabs and cautioned them to be as \nquiet as mice. Since they were well behaved and obedient little rabs, they \ndid just as their mother told them. \n\n    "I left my big stick beside the old oak tree," cried Papa Rabbit under \nhis breath. "What shall we do?" \n\n    "Sniff! Sniff! Sniff!" went Sly Fox again, scratching up the earth by \nthe old hollow tree as he began to dig furiously. The poor little Rabbit \nfamily sat still and frightened, their hearts thumping, their paws shaking, \nand their eyes bulging with panic. Suddenly in the distance they heard the \n"Toot! Toot!Toot!" of horns, and the "Woof! Woof! Woof!" of barking dogs. \n\n    Papa Rabbit whispered, "Fox hunters!" as his heart gave a bound of \nrelief. \n\n    Nearer and nearer came the baying of the hounds and the music of the \nhorns. Old Sly Fox was so busily digging that he failed to hear at first, \nbut suddenly he stopped digging, and threw back his ears to listen. Then he \nquickly jumped away from the log where the Rabbit family lived and started \nrunning. \n\n    But the hounds were right after him, baying loudly with all their might. \nThe horses\' feet beat out an excited rhythm as the red-coated fox hunters \nurged them on in the chase. Up hill, over the meadows they ran. \n\n    Sly Fox was now running for his life, but the dogs were getting closer \nand closer. He jumped across the brook and spied a hole among some bushes. \nInto this he slid, and as the dogs went down the side of the stream of water \nbefore they jumped across they lost his scent. Sly Fox quickly ran out of \nthe hole and took off in the opposite direction from the way the dogs were \ngoing. He had been so frightened and so near death that he resolved to \nhimself never to bother the Rabbit family again. \n\n    Meanwhile, when Papa Rabbit had heard the hounds start the chase, he \nturned to Mama Rabbit and cried, "Safe at last! Call our little rabs for \nprayers of thanksgiving and praise to our Father which art in heaven." \n\n    After prayers, Mama Rabbit hustled about making mint tea for her and \nPapa Rabbit, and hot chocolate piled high with whipped cream for the little \nrabs. After that time they Lived happily among the great whispering pines, \nnever bothered by old Sly Fox.\n                                                          --Beulah Murrelle \n\n', ':.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:\n         -----=====Earth\'s Dreamlands=====-----\n           (313)558-5024 {14.4} (313)558-5517\n              A BBS for text file junkies\n              RPGNet GM File Archive Site\n.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.\n\n            The Adveniure of the Three Gables\n\n  I don\'t think that any of my adventures with Mr. Sherlock\nHolmes opened quite so abruptly, or so dramatically, as that\nwhich I associate with The Three Gables. I had not seen Holmes\nfor some days and had no idea of the new channel into which his\nactivities had been directed. He was in a chatty mood that\nmorning, however, and had just settled me into the well-worn\nlow armchair on one side of the fire, while he had curled down\nwith his pipe in his mouth upon the opposite chair, when our\nvisitor arrived. If I had said that a mad bull had arrived it would\ngive a clearer impression of what occurred.\n  The door had flown open and a huge negro had burst into the\nroom. He would have been a comic figure if he had not been\nterrific, for he was dressed in a very loud gray check suit with a\nflowing salmon-coloured tie. His broad face and flattened nose\nwere thrust forward, as his sullen dark eyes, with a smouldering\ngleam of malice in them, turned from one of us to the other.\n  "Which of you gen\'l\'men is Masser Holmes?" he asked.\n  Holmes raised his pipe with a languid smile.\n  "Oh! it\'s you, is it?" said our visitor, coming with an un-\npleasant, stealthy step round the angle of the table. "See here,\nMasser Holmes, you keep your hands out of other folks\' busi-\nness. Leave folks to manage their own affairs. Got that, Masser\nHolmes?"\n  "Keep on talking," said Holmes. "It\'s fine."\n  "Oh! it\'s fine, is it?" growled the savage. "It won\'t be so\ndamn fine if I have to trim you up a bit. I\'ve handled your kind\nbefore now, and they didn\'t look fine when I was through with\nthem. Look at that, Masser Holmes!"\n  He swung a huge knotted lump of a fist under my friend\'s\nnose. Holmes examined it closely with an air of great interest.\n  "Were you born so?" he asked. "Or did it come by degrees?"\n  It may have been the icy coolness of my friend, or it may have\nbeen the slight clatter which I made as I picked up the poker. In\nany case, our visitor\'s manner became less flamboyant.\n  "Well, I\'ve given you fair warnin\'," said he. "I\'ve a friend\nthat\'s interested out Harrow way -- you know what I\'m meaning --\nand he don\'t intend to have no buttin\' in by you. Got that? You\nain\'t the law, and I ain\'t the law either, and if you come in I\'ll\nbe on hand also. Don\'t you forget it."\n  "I\'ve wanted to meet you for some time," said Holmes. "I\nwon\'t ask you to sit down, for I don\'t like the smell of you, but\naren\'t you Steve Dixie, the bruiser?"\n  "That\'s my name, Masser Holmes, and you\'ll get put through\nit for sure if you give me any lip."\n  "It is certainly the last thing you need," said Holmes, staring\nat our visitor\'s hideous mouth. "But it was the killing of young\nPerkins outside the Holborn -- Bar What! you\'re not going?"\n  The negro had sprung back, and his face was leaden. "I won\'t\nlisten to no such talk," said he. "What have I to do with this \'ere\nPerkins, Masser Holmes? I was trainin\' at the Bull Ring in\nBirmingham when this boy done gone get into trouble."\n  "Yes, you\'ll tell the magistrate about it, Steve," said Holmes.\n"I\'ve been watching you and Barney Stockdale --"\n  "So help me the Lord! It was\nthat same gen\'l\'man that you have just done gone mention."\n  "And who set him on to it?"\n  "S\'elp me. I don\'t know, Masser Holmes. He just say,\n\'Steve, you go see Mr. Holmes, and tell him his life ain\'t\nsafe if he go down Harrow way.\' That\'s the whole truth."\nWithout waiting for any further questioning, our visitor bolted\nout of the room almost as precipitately as he had entered.\nHolmes knocked out the ashes of his pipe with a quiet chuckle.\n  "I am glad you were not forced to break his woolly head,\nWatson. I observed your manoeuvres with the poker. But he is\nreally rather a harmless fellow, a great muscular, foolish, blus-\ntering baby, and easily cowed, as you have seen. He is one\nof the Spencer John gang and has taken part in some dirty\nwork of late which I may clear up when I have time. His\nimmediate principal, Barney, is a more astute person. They\nspecialize in assaults, intimidation, and the like. What I want\nto know is, who is at the back of them on this panicular\noccasion?"\n  "But why do they want to intimidate you?"\n  "It is this Harrow Weald case. It decides me to look into the\nmatter, for if it is worth anyone\'s while to take so much trouble,\nthere must be something in it."\n  "But what is it?"\n  "I was going to tell you when we had this comic interlude.\nHere is Mrs. Maberley\'s note. If you care to come with me we\nwill wire her and go out at once."\n\n     DEAR MR. SHERLOCK HOLMES [I read]:\n       I have had a succession of strange incidents occur to me\n     in connection with this house, and I should much value your\n     advice. You would find me at home any time to-morrow.\n     The house is within a short walk of the Weald Station. I\n     believe that my late husband, Mortimer Maberley, was one\n     of your early clients.\n                                            Yours faithfully,\n                                               MARY MABERLEY.\n\n  The address was "The Three Gables, Harrow Weald."\n  "So that\'s that!" said Holmes. "And now, if you can spare\nthe time, Watson, we will get upon our way."\n  A short railway journey, and a shorter drive, brought us to the\nhouse, a brick and timber villa, standing in its own acre of\nundeveloped grassland. Three small projections above. the upper\nwindows made a feeble attempt to justify its name. Behind was a\ngrove of melancholy, half-grown pines, and the whole aspect of\nthe place was poor and depressing. None the less, we found the\nhouse to be well furnished, and the lady who received us was a\nmost engaging elderly person, who bore every mark of refine-\nment and culture.\n  "I remember your husband well, madam," said Holmes,\n"though it is some years since he used my services in some\ntrifling matter."\n  "Probably you would be more familiar with the name of my\nson Douglas."\n  Holmes looked at her with great interest.\n  "Dear me! He was attache at Rome, and he\ndied there of pneumonia last month."\n  "I am sorry. One could not connect death with such a man. I\nhave never known anyone so vitally alive. In a single month I seemed to see\nmy gallant boy turn into a worn-out cynical man."\n  "A love affair -- a woman?"\n  "Or a fiend. Well, it was not to talk of my poor lad that I\nasked you to come, Mr. Holmes."\n  "Dr. Watson and I are at your service."\n  "There have been some very strange happenings. It seemed to me\nvery strange as there are several empty houses on the market\nwhich appear to be equally eligible, but naturally I was interested\nin what he said. I therefore named a price which was five\nhundred pounds more than I gave. He at once closed with the\noffer, but added that his client desired to buy the furniture as\nwell and would I put a price upon it. Some of this furniture is\nfrom my old home, and it is, as you see, very good, so that I\nnamed a good round sum. To this also he at once agreed. He said to me, \'This is a very strange document. Language!"\n  "I am clearing out of here. I\'ve had enough of you all. I\'ll\nsend for my box to-morrow." She flounced for the door.\n  "Good-bye, Susan. Paregoric is the stuff.... Now," he\ncontinued, turning suddenly from lively to severe when the door\nhad closed behind the flushed and angry woman, "this gang\nmeans business. Look how close they play the game. Your letter\nto me had the 10 P.M. postmark. And yet Susan passes the word\nto Barney. Barney has time to go to his employer and get\ninstructions; he or she -- I incline to the latter from Susan\'s grin\nwhen she thought I had blundered -- forms a plan. Who had the house before you?"\n  "A retired sea captain called Ferguson."\n  "Anything remarkable about him?"\n  "Not that ever I heard of."\n  "I was wondering whether he could have buried something.\nOf course, when people bury treasure nowadays they do it in the\nPost-Office bank. No, as I read it, there is something\nwhich you do not know that you have, and which you would not\ngive up if you did know."\n  "That is how I read it," said I.\n  "Dr. Watson agrees, so that settles it."\n  "Well, Mr. Holmes, what can it be?"\n  "Let us see whether by this purely mental analysis we can get\nit to a finer point. None were happier than the three little pigs, and they\neasily made friends with everyone. Wherever they went, they were given a warm \nwelcome, but as summer drew to a close, they realized that folk were drifting\nback to their usual jobs, and preparing for winter. Autumn came and it began\nto rain. The three little pigs started to feel they needed a real home. Sadly\nthey knew that the fun was over now and they must set to work like the others,\nor they\'d be left in the cold and rain, with no roof over their heads. They\ntalked about what to do, but each decided for himself. The laziest little pig\nsaid he\'d build a straw hut.\n   "It wlll only take a day,\' he said. The others disagreed.\n   "It\'s too fragile," they said disapprovingly, but he refused to listen. Not\nquite so lazy, the second little pig went in search of planks of seasoned\nwood.\n   "Clunk! Clunk! Clunk!" It took him two days to nail them together. But the\nthird little pig did not like the wooden house.\n   "That\'s not the way to build a house!" he said. "It takes time, patience \nand hard work to buiid a house that is strong enough to stand up to wind, \nrain, and snow, and most of all, protect us from the wolf!"\n   The days went by, and the wisest little pig\'s house took shape, brick by\nbrick. From time to time, his brothers visited him, saying with a chuckle:\n   "Why are you working so hard? Why don\'t you come and play?" But the\nstubborn bricklayer pig just said "no".\n   "I shall finish my house first. It must be solid and sturdy. And then I\'ll\ncome and play!" he said. "I shall not be foolish like you! For he who laughs\nlast, laughs longest!"\n   It was the wisest little pig that found the tracks of a big wolf in the\nneighbourhood.\n   The little pigs rushed home in alarm. Along came the wolf, scowling \nfiercely at the laziest pig\'s straw hut.\n   "Come out!" ordered the wolf, his mouth watering. I want to speak to you!"\n   "I\'d rather stay where I am!" replied the little pig in a tiny voice.\n   "I\'ll make you come out!" growled the wolf angrily, and puffing out his\nchest, he took a very deep breath. Then he blew wlth all his might, right onto\nthe house. And all the straw the silly pig had heaped against some thin poles,\nfell down in the great blast. Excited by his own cleverness, the wolf did not\nnotice that the little pig had slithered out from underneath the heap of\nstraw, and was dashing towards his brother\'s wooden house. When he realized \nthat the little pig was escaping, the wolf grew wild with rage.\n   "Come back!" he roared, trying to catch the pig as he ran into the wooden \nhouse. The other little pig greeted his brother, shaking like a leaf.\n   "I hope this house won\'t fall down! Let\'s lean against the door so he can\'t\nbreak in!"\n   Outside, the wolf could hear the little pigs\' words. Starving as he was, at\nthe idea of a two-course meal, he rained blows on the door.\n   "Open up! Open up! I only want to speak to you!"\n   Inside, the two brothers wept in fear and did their best to hold the door\nfast against the blows. Then the furious wolf braced himself a new effort: he\ndrew in a really enormous breath, and went ... WHOOOOO! The wooden house\ncollapsed like a pack of cards.\n   Luckily, the wisest little pig had been watching the scene from the window\nof his own brick house, and he rapidly opened the door to his fleeing \nbrothers. And not a moment too soon, for the wolf was already hammering \nfuriously on the door. This time, the wolf had grave doubts. This house had a\nmuch more solid air than the others. He blew once, he blew again and then for\na third time. But all was in vain. For the house did not budge an lnch. The\nthree little pigs watched him and their fear began to fade. Quite exhausted by\nhis efforts, the wolf decided to try one of his tricks. He scrambled up a\nnearby ladder, on to the roof to have a look at the chimney. However, the\nwisest little pig had seen thls ploy, and he quickly said:\n   "Quick! Light the fire!" With his long legs thrust down the chimney, the\nwolf was not sure if he should slide down the black hole. It wouldn\'tbe easy\nto get in, but the sound of the little pigs\' voices below only made him feel\nhungrier.\n   "I\'m dying of hunger! I\'m goin to try and get down." And he let himself \ndrop. Never again will I go down a chimneyl" he squealed, as he\ntried to put out the flames in his tail. Then he ran away as fast as he could.\n   The three happy little pigs, dancing round and round the yard, began to \nsing:\n   "Tra-la-la! Tra-la-la! The wicked black wolf will never come back...!"\n   From that terrible day on, the wisest little pig\'s brothers set to work\nwith a will. In less than no time, up went the two new brick houses. The wolf\ndid return once to roam in the neighbourhood, but when he caught sight of\nthree chimneys, he remembered the terrible pain of a burnt tail, and he left\nfor good.\n   Now safe and happy, the wisest little pig called to his brothers:\n   "No more work! Bordeaux  (S.R.)  -\n\n\n\x1a", ':.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:\n         -----=====Earth\'s Dreamlands=====-----\n           (313)558-5024 {14.4} (313)558-5517\n              A BBS for text file junkies\n              RPGNet GM File Archive Site\n.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.:.\n\n             The Adventure of the Three Students\n\n  It was in the year \'95 that a combination of events, into which I\nneed not enter, caused Mr. Sherlock Holmes and myself to spend\nsome weeks in one of our great university towns, and it was\nduring this time that the small but instructive adventure which I\nam about to relate befell us. It will be obvious that any details\nwhich would help the reader exactly to identify the college or the\ncriminal would be injudicious and offensive. So painful a scan-\ndal may well be allowed to die out. With due discretion the\nincident itself may, however, be described, since it serves to\nillustrate some of those qualities for which my friend was re-\nmarkable. I will endeavour, in my statement, to avoid such terms\nas would serve to limit the events to any particular place, or give\na clue as to the people concerned.\n  We were residing at the time in furnished lodgings close to a\nlibrary where Sherlock Holmes was pursuing some laborious\nresearches in early English charters -- researches which led to\nresults so striking that they may be the subject of one of my\nfuture narratives. Here it was that one evening we received a\nvisit from an acquaintance, Mr. Hilton Soames, tutor and lec-\nturer at the College of St. Luke\'s. Mr. Soames was a tall, spare\nman, of a nervous and excitable temperament. I had always\nknown him to be restless in his manner, but on this particular\noccasion he was in such a state of uncontrollable agitation that it\nwas clear something very unusual had occurred.\n  "I trust, Mr. Holmes, that you can spare me a few hours of\nyour valuable time. We have had a very painful incident at St.\nLuke\'s, and really, but for the happy chance of your being in\ntown, I should have been at a loss what to do."\n  "I am very busy just now, and I desire no distractions," my\nfriend answered. "I should much prefer that you called in the aid\nof the police."\n  "No, no, my dear sir; such a course is utterly impossible.\nWhen once the law is evoked it cannot be stayed again, and this\nis just one of those cases where, for the credit of the college, it is\nmost essential to avoid scandal. Your discretion is as well known\nas your powers, and you are the one man in the world who can\nhelp me. I beg you, Mr. Holmes, to do what you can."\n  My friend\'s temper had not improved since he had been\ndeprived of the congenial surroundings of Baker Street. Without\nhis scrapbooks, his chemicals, and his homely untidiness, he was\nan uncomfortable man. He shrugged his shoulders in ungracious\nacquiescence, while our visitor in hurried words and with much\nexcitable gesticulation poured forth his story.\n  "I must explain to you, Mr. Holmes, that to-morrow is the\nfirst day of the examination for the Fortescue Scholarship. I am\none of the examiners. My subject is Greek, and the first of the\npapers consists of a large passage of Greek translation which the\ncandidate has not seen. This passage is printed on the examina-\ntion paper, and it would naturally be an immense advantage if\nthe candidate could prepare it in advance. For this reason, great\ncare is taken to keep the paper secret.\n  "To-day, about three o\'clock, the proofs of this paper arrived\nfrom the printers. The exercise consists of half a chapter of\nThucydides. I had to read it over carefully, as the text must be\nabsolutely correct. At four-thirty my task was not yet completed.\nI had, however, promised to take tea in a friend\'s rooms, so I\nleft the proof upon my desk. I was absent rather more than an\nhour.\n  "You are aware, Mr. Holmes, that our college doors are\ndouble -- a green baize one within and a heavy oak one without.\nAs I approached my outer door, I was amazed to see a key in it.\nFor an instant I imagined that I had left my own there, but on\nfeeling in my pocket I found that it was all right. The only\nduplicate which existed, so far as I knew, was that which\nbelonged to my servant, Bannister -- a man who has looked after\nmy room for ten years, and whose honesty is absolutely above\nsuspicion. I found that the key was indeed his, that he had\nentered my room to know if I wanted tea, and that he had very\ncarelessly left the key in the door when he came out. His visit to\nmy room must have been within a very few minutes of my\nleaving it. His forgetfulness about the key would have mattered\nlittle upon any other occasion, but on this one day it has pro-\nduced the most deplorable consequences.\n  "The moment I looked at my table, I was aware that someone\nhad rummaged among my papers. The proof was in three long\nslips. I had left them all together. Now, I found that one of them\nwas lying on the floor, one was on the side table near the\nwindow, and the third was where I had left it."\n  Holmes stirred for the first time.\n  "The first page on the floor, the second in the window, the\nthird where you left it," said he.\n  "Exactly, Mr. Holmes. You amaze me. How could you possi-\nbly know that?"\n  "Pray continue your very interesting statement."\n  "For an instant I imagined that Bannister had taken the unpar-\ndonable liberty of examining my papers. He denied it, however,\nwith the utmost earnestness, and I am convinced that he was\nspeaking the truth. The alternative was that someone passing had\nobserved the key in the door, had known that I was out, and had\nentered to look at the papers. A large sum of money is at stake,\nfor the scholarship is a very valuable one, and an unscrupulous\nman might very well run a risk in order to gain an advantage\nover his fellows.\n  "Bannister was very much upset by the incident. He had\nnearly fainted when we found that the papers had undoubtedly\nbeen tampered with. I gave him a little brandy and left him\ncollapsed in a chair, while I made a most careful examination of\nthe room. I soon saw that the intruder had left other traces of his\npresence besides the rumpled papers. On the table in the window\nwere several shreds from a pencil which had been sharpened. A\nbroken tip of lead was lying there also. Evidently the rascal had\ncopied the paper in a great hurry, had broken his pencil, and had\nbeen compelled to put a fresh point to it."\n  "Excellent!" said Holmes, who was recovering his good-\nhumour as his attention became more engrossed by the case.\n"Fortune has been your friend."\n  "This was not all. I have a new writing-table with a fine\nsurface of red leather. I am prepared to swear, and so is Bannis-\nter, that it was smooth and unstained. Now I found a clean cut in\nit about three inches long -- not a mere scratch, but a positive cut.\nNot only this, but on the table I found a small ball of black\ndough or clay, with specks of something which looks like saw-\ndust in it. I am convinced that these marks were left by the man\nwho rifled the papers. There were no footmarks and no other\nevidence as to his identity. I was at my wit\'s end, when suddenly\nthe happy thought occurred to me that you were in the town, and\nI came straight round to put the matter into your hands. Do help\nme, Mr. Holmes. You see my dilemma. Either I must find the\nman or else the examination must be postponed until fresh papers\nare prepared, and since this cannot be done without explanation,\nthere will ensue a hideous scandal, which will throw a cloud not\nonly on the college, but on the university. Above all things, I\ndesire to settle the matter quietly and discreetly."\n  "I shall be happy to look into it and to give you such advice\nas I can," said Holmes, rising and putting on his overcoat.\n"The case is not entirely devoid of interest. Had anyone visited\nyou in your room after the papers came to you?"\n  "Yes, young Daulat Ras, an Indian student, who lives on the\nsame stair, came in to ask me some particulars about the exami-\nnation."\n  "For which he was entered?"\n  "Yes."\n  "And the papers were on your table?"\n  "To the best of my belief, they were rolled up."\n  "But might be recognized as proofs?"\n  "Possibly."\n  "No one else in your room?"\n  "No."\n  "Did anyone know that these proofs would be there?"\n  "No one save the printer."\n  "Did this man Bannister know?"\n  "No, certainly not. No one knew."\n  "Where is Bannister now?"\n  "He was very ill, poor fellow. I left him collapsed in the\nchair. I was in such a hurry to come to you."\n  "You left your door open?"\n  "I locked up the papers first."\n  "Then it amounts to this, Mr. Soames: that, unless the Indian\nstudent recognized the roll as being proofs, the man who tam-\npered with them came upon them accidentally without knowing\nthat they were there."\n  "So it seems to me."\n  Holmes gave an enigmatic smile.\n  "Well," said he. "let us go round. Not one of your cases.\nWatson -- mental, not physical. All right; come if you want to.\nNow, Mr. Soames -- at your disposal!"\n  The sitting-room of our client opened by a long, low, latticed\nwindow on to the ancient lichen-tinted court of the old college.\nA Gothic arched door led to a worn stone staircase. On the\nground floor was the tutor\'s room. Above were three students,\none on each story. It was already twilight when we reached the\nscene of our problem. Holmes halted and looked earnestly at the\nwindow. Then he approached it, and, standing on tiptoe with his\nneck craned, he looked into the room.\n  "He must have entered through the door. There is no opening\nexcept the one pane," said our learned guide.\n  "Dear me!" said Holmes, and he smiled in a singular way as\nhe glanced at our companion. "Well, if there is nothing to be\nlearned here, we had best go inside."\n  The lecturer unlocked the outer door and ushered us into his\nroom. We stood at the entrance while Holmes made an examina-\ntion of the carpet.\n  "I am afraid there are no signs here," said he. "One could\nhardly hope for any upon so dry a day. Your servant seems to\nhave quite recovered. You left him in a chair, you say. Which\nchair?"\n  "By the window there."\n  "I see. Near this little table. You can come in now. I have\nfinished with the carpet. Let us take the little table first. Of\ncourse, what has happened is very clear. The man entered and\ntook the papers, sheet by sheet, from the central table. He\ncarried them over to the window table, because from there he\ncould see if you came across the courtyard, and so could effect\nan escape."\n  "As a matter of fact, he could not," said Soames, "for I\nentered by the side door."\n  "Ah, that\'s good! Well, anyhow, that was in his mind. Let\nme see the three strips. No finger impressions -- no! Well he\ncarried over this one first, and he copied it. How long wouid it\ntake him to do that, using every possible contraction? A quarter\nof an hour, not less. Then he tossed it down and seized the next.\nHe was in the midst of that when your return caused him to make\na very hurried retreat -- very hurried, since he had not time to\nreplace the papers which would tell you that he had been there.\nYou were not aware of any hurrying feet on the stair as you\nentered the outer door?"\n  "No, I can\'t say I was."\n  "Well, he wrote so furiously that he broke his pencil, and\nhad, as you observe, to sharpen it again. This is of interest,\nWatson. The pencil was not an ordinary one. It was above the\nusual size, with a soft lead, the outer colour was dark blue, the\nmaker\'s name was printed in silver lettering, and the piece\nremaining is only about an inch and a half long. Look for such a\npencil, Mr. Soames, and you have got your man. When I add\nthat he possesses a large and very blunt knife, you have an\nadditional aid."\n  Mr. Soames was somewhat overwhelmed by this flood of\ninformation. "I can follow the other points," said he, "but\nreally, in this matter of the length --"\n  Holmes held out a small chip with the letters NN and a space\nof clear wood after them.\n  "You see?"\n  "No, I fear that even now --"\n  "Watson, I have always done you an injustice. There are\nothers. What could this NN be? It is at the end of a word. You\nare aware that Johann Faber is the most common maker\'s name.\nIs it not clear that there is just as much of the pencil left as\nusually follows the Johann?" He held the small table sideways to\nthe electric light. "I was hoping that if the paper on which he\nwrote was thin, some trace of it might come through upon this\npolished surface. No, I see nothing. I don\'t think there is any-\nthing more to be learned here. Now for the central table. This\nsmall pellet is, I presume, the black, doughy mass you spoke of.\nRoughly pyramidal in shape and hollowed out, I perceive. As\nyou say, there appear to be grains of sawdust in it. Dear me, this\nis very interesting. And the cut -- a positive tear, I see. It began\nwith a thin scratch and ended in a jagged hole. I am much\nindebted to you for directing my attention to this case, Mr.\nSoames. Where does that door lead to?"\n  "To my bedroom."\n  "Have you been in it since your adventure?"\n  "No, I came straight away for you."\n  "I should like to have a glance round. What a charming,\nold-fashioned room! Perhaps you will kindly wait a minute, until\nI have examined the floor. No, I see nothing. What about this\ncurtain? You hang your clothes behind it. If anyone were forced\nto conceal himself in this room he must do it there, since the bed\nis too low and the wardrobe too shallow. No one there, I\nsuppose?"\n  As Holmes drew the curtain I was aware, from some little\nrigidity and alertness of his attitude, that he was prepared for an\nemergency. As a matter of fact, the drawn curtain disclosed\nnothing but three or four suits of clothes hanging from a line of\npegs. Holmes turned away, and stooped suddenly to the floor.\n  "Halloa! What\'s this?" said he.\n  It was a small pyramid of black, putty-like stuff, exactly like\nthe one upon the table of the study. Holmes held it out on his\nopen palm in the glare of the electric light.\n  "Your visitor seems to have left traces in your bedroom as\nwell as in your sitting-room, Mr. Soames."\n  "What could he have wanted there?"\n  "I think it is clear enough. You came back by an unexpected\nway, and so he had no warning until you were at the very door.\nWhat could he do? He caught up everything which would betray\nhim, and he rushed into your bedroom to conceal himself."\n  "Good gracious, Mr. Holmes, do you mean to tell me that, all\nthe time I was talking to Bannister in this room, we had the man\nprisoner if we had only known it?"\n  "So I read it."\n  "Surely there is another alternative, Mr. Holmes. I don\'t\nknow whether you observed my bedroom window?"\n  "Lattice-paned, lead framework, three separate windows, one\nswinging on hinge, and large enough to admit a man."\n  "Exactly. And it looks out on an angle of the courtyard so as\nto be partly invisible. The man might have effected his entrance\nthere, left traces as he passed through the bedroom, and finally,\nfinding the door open, have escaped that way."\n  Holmes shook his head impatiently.\n  "Let us be practical," said he. "I understand you to say that\nthere are three students who use this stair, and are in the habit of\npassing your door?"\n  "Yes, there are."\n  "And they are all in for this examination?"\n  "Yes."\n  "Have you any reason to suspect any one of them more than\nthe others?"\n  Soames hesitated.\n  "It is a very delicate question." said he. "One hardly likes to\nthrow suspicion where there are no proofs."\n  "Let us hear the suspicions. I will look after the proofs."\n  "I will tell you, then, in a few words the character of the three\nmcn who inhabit these rooms. The lower of the three is Gilchrist,\na fine scholar and athletc, plays in the Rugby team and the\ncricket team for the college, and got his Blue for the hurdles and\nthe long jump. He is a fine, manly fellow. His father was the\nnotorious Sir Jabez Gilchrist, who ruined himself on the turf. My\nscholar has been left very poor, but he is hard-working and\nindustrious. He will do well.\n  "The second floor is inhabited by Daulat Ras, the Indian. He\nis a quiet, inscrutable fellow; as most of those Indians are. He is\nwell up in his work, though his Greek is his weak subject. He is\nsteady and methodical.\n  "The top floor belongs to Miles McLaren. He is a brilliant\nfellow when he chooses to work -- one of the brightest intellects\nof the university; but he is wayward, dissipated, and unprinci-\npled. He was nearly expelled over a card scandal in his first\nyear. He has been idling all this term, and he must look forward\nwith dread to the examination."\n  "Then it is he whom you suspect?"\n  "I dare not go so far as that. But, of the three, he is perhaps the\nleast unlikely."\n  "Exactly. Now, Mr. Soames, let us have a look at your\nservant, Bannister."\n  He was a little, white-faced, clean-shaven, grizzly-haired fel-\nlow of fifty. He was still suffering from this sudden disturbance\nof the quiet routine of his life. His plump face was twitching\nwith his nervousness, and his fingers could not keep still.\n  "We are investigating this unhappy business, Bannister," said\nhis master.\n  "Yes, sir."\n  "I understand," said Holmes, "that you left your key in the\ndoor?"\n  "Yes, sir."\n  "Was it not very extraordinary that you should do this on the\nvery day when there were these papers inside?"\n  "It was most unfortunate. sir. But I have occasionally done\nthe same thing at other times."\n  "When did you enter the room?"\n  It was about half-past four. That is Mr. Soames\'s tea time."\n  "How long did you stay?"\n  "When I saw that he was absent. I withdrew at once."\n  "Did you look at these papers on the table?"\n  "No, sir certainly not."\n  "How came you to leave the key in the door?"\n  "I had the tea-tray in my hand. I thought I would come back\nfor the key. Then I forgot."\n  "Has the outer door a spring lock?"\n  "No, sir."\n  "Then it was open all the time?"\n  "Yes, sir."\n  "Anyone in the room could get out?"\n  "Yes, sir."\n  "When Mr. Soames returned and called for you, you were\nvery much disturbed?"\n  "Yes, sir. Such a thing has never happened during the many\nyears that I have been here. I nearly fainted, sir."\n  "So I understand. Where were you when you began to feel\nbad?"\n  "Where was I, sir? Why, here, near the door."\n  "That is singular, because you sat down in that chair over\nyonder near the corner. Why did you pass these other chairs?"\n  "I don\'t know, sir, it didn\'t matter to me where I sat."\n  "I really don\'t think he knew much about it, Mr. Holmes. He\nwas looking very bad -- quite ghastly."\n  "You stayed here when your master left?"\n  "Only for a minute or so. Then I locked the door and went to\nmy room."\n  "Whom do you suspect?"\n  "Oh, I would not venture to say, sir. I don\'t believe there is\nany gentleman in this university who is capable of profiting by\nsuch an action. No, sir, I\'ll not believe it."\n  "Thank you, that will do," said Holmes. "Oh, one more\nword. You have not mentioned to any of the three gentlemen\nwhom you attend that anything is amiss?"\n  "No, sir -- not a word."\n  "You haven\'t seen any of them?"\n  "No, sir."\n  "Very good. Now, Mr. Soames, we will take a walk in the\nquadrangle, if you please."\n  Three yellow squares of light shone above us in the gathering\ngloom.\n  "Your three birds are all in their nests," said Holmes, looking\nup. "Halloa! What\'s that? One of them seems restless enough."\n  It was the Indian, whose dark silhouette appeared suddenly\nupon his blind. He was pacing swiftly up and down his room.\n  "I should like to have a peep at each of them," said Holmes.\n"Is it possible?"\n  "No difficulty in the world," Soames answered. "This set of\nrooms is quite the oldest in the college, and it is not unusual for\nvisitors to go over them. Come along, and I will personally\nconduct you."\n  "No names, please!" said Holmes, as we knocked at Gilchrist\'s\ndoor. A tall, flaxen-haired, slim young fellow opened it, and\nmade us welcome when he understood our errand. There were\nsome really curious pieces of mediaeval domestic architecture\nwithin. Holmes was so charmed with one of them that he insisted\non drawing it in his notebook, broke his pencil, had to borrow\none from our host, and finally borrowed a knife to sharpen his\nown. The same curious accident happened to him in the rooms of\nthe Indian -- a silent, little, hook-nosed fellow, who eyed us\naskance, and was obviously glad when Holmes\'s architectural\nstudies had come to an end. I could not see that in either case\nHolmes had come upon the clue for which he was searching.\nOnly at the third did our visit prove abortive. The outer door\nwould not open to our knock, and-nothing more substantial than\na torrent of bad language came from behind it. "I don\'t care who\nyou are. You can go to blazes!" roared the angry voice. "To-\nmorrow\'s the exam, and I won\'t be drawn by anyone."\n  "A rude fellow," said our guide, flushing with anger as we\nwithdrew down the stair. "Of course, he did not realize that it\nwas I who was knocking, but none the less his conduct was very\nuncourteous, and, indeed, under the circumstances rather\nsuspicious."\n  Holmes\'s response was a curious one.\n  "Can you tell me his exact height?" he asked.\n  "Really, Mr. Holmes, I cannot undertake to say. He is taller\nthan the Indian, not so tall as Gilchrist. I suppose five foot six\nwould be about it."\n  "That is very important," said Holmes. "And now, Mr.\nSoames, I wish you good-night."\n  Our guide cried aloud in his astonishment and dismay. "Good\ngracious, Mr. Holmes, you are surely not going to leave me in\nthis abrupt fashion! You don\'t seem to realize the position.\nTo-morrow is the examination. I must take some definite action\nto-night. I cannot allow the examination to be held if one of the\npapers has been tampered with. The situation must be faced."\n  "You must leave it as it is. I shall drop round early to-morrow\nmorning and chat the matter over. It is possible that I may be in\na position then to indicate some course of action. Meanwhile,\nyou change nothing -- nothing at all."\n  "Very good, Mr. Holmes."\n  "You can be perfectly easy in your mind. We shall certainly\nfind some way out of your difficulties. I will take the black clay\nwith me, also the pencil cuttings. Good-bye."\n  When we were out in the darkness of the quadrangle, we again\nlooked up at the windows. The Indian still paced his room. The\nothers were invisible.\n  "Well, Watson, what do you think of it?" Holmes asked, as\nwe came out into the main street. "Quite a little parlour game -- \nsort of three-card trick, is it not? There are your three men. It\nmust be one of them. You take your choice. Which is yours?"\n  "The foul-mouthed fellow at the top. He is the one with the\nworst record. And yet that Indian was a sly fellow also. Why\nshould he be pacing his room all the time?"\n  "There is nothing in that. Many men do it when they are\ntrying to learn anything by heart."\n  "He looked at us in a queer way."\n  "So would you, if a flock of strangers came in on you when\nyou were preparing for an examination next day, and every\nmoment was of value. No, I see nothing in that. Pencils, too,\nand knives -- all was satisfactory. But that fellow does puzzle\nme."\n  "Who?"\n  "Why, Bannister, the servant. What\'s his game in the matter?"\n  "He impressed me as being a perfectly honest man."\n  "So he did me. That\'s the puzzling part. Why should a\nperfectly honest man -- Well, well, here\'s a large stationer\'s. We\nshall begin our researches here."\n  There were only four stationers of any consequences in the\ntown, and at each Holmes produced his pencil chips, and bid\nhigh for a duplicate. All were agreed that one could be ordered,\nbut that it was not a usual size of pencil, and that it was seldom\nkept in stock. My friend did not appear to be depressed by his\nfailure, but shrugged his shoulders in half-humorous resignation.\n  "No good, my dear Watson. This, the best and only final\nclue, has run to nothing. But, indeed, I have little doubt that we\ncan build up a sufficient case without it. By Jove! my dear\nfellow, it is nearly nine, and the landlady babbled of green peas\nat seven-thirty. Each morning he set off \nsinging to work, and when he came home in the evening, a plate of hot steaming \nsoup was always waiting for him. \n   One day, however, he had a strange surprise. He came upon a big fir tree \nwith strange open holes on the trunk. It looked somehow different from the \nother trees, and just as he was about to chop it down, the alarmed face of an \nelf popped out of a hole.\n   "What\'s all this banging?" asked the elf. "You\'re not thinking of cutting \ndown this tree, are you? It\'s my home. I live here!" The woodcutter dropped \nhis axe in astonlshment.\n   "Well, I . . ." he stammered.\n   "With all the other trees there are in this forest, you have to pick this \none. Lucky I was in, or I would have found myself homeless."\n   Taken aback at these words, the woodcutter qulckly recovered, for after all\nthe elf was quite tiny, while he himself was a big hefty chap, and he boldly \nreplied: "I\'ll cut down any tree I like, so . . ." \n   "All right! All right!" broke in the elf. "Shall we put it this way: if you\ndon\'t cut down this tree, I grant you three wishes. Agreed?" The woodcutter \nscratched his head. \n   "Three wishes, you say? Yes, I agree." And he began to hack at another \ntree. As he worked and sweated at his task, the woodcutter kept thinking about\nthe magic wishes. \n   "I\'ll see what my wife thinks..."\n   The woodcutter\'s wife was busily cleaning a pot outside the house when her \nhusband arrived. Grabbing her round the waist, he twirled her in delight.\n   "Hooray! Hooray! Our luck is in!" \n   The woman could not understand why her husband was so pleased with himself \nand she shrugged herself free. Later, however, over a glass of fine wine at \nthe table, the woodcutter told his wife of his meeting with the elf, and she \ntoo began to picture the wonderful things that the elf\'s three wishes might \ngive them. The woodcutter\'s wife took a first sip of wine from her husband\'s \nglass.\n   "Nice," she said, smacking her lips. "I wish I had a string of sausages to \ngo with it, though..."\n   Instantly she bit her tongue, but too late. Out of the air appeared the \nsausages while the woodcutter stuttered with rage.\n   ". . . what have you done! Sausages . . . What a stupid waste of a wish! \nYou foollsh woman. I wish they would stick up your nose!" No sooner sald than\ndone. For the sausages leapt up and stuck fast to the end of the woman\'s nose.\nThis time, the woodcutter\'s wife flew into a rage.\n   "You idiot, what have you done? With all the things we could have wished \nfor . . ." The mortified woodcutter, who had just repeated his wife\'s own \nmistake, exclaimed:\n   "I\'d chop . . ." Luckily he stopped himself in time, realizing with horror \nthat he\'d been on the point of having his tongue chopped off. As his wife \ncomplained and blamed him, the poor man burst out laughing.\n   "If only you knew how funny you look with those sausages on the end of your\nnose!" Now that really upset the woodcutter\'s wife. She hadn\'t thought of her \nlooks. She tried to tug away the sausages but they would not budge. She pulled \nagain and again, but in vain. The sausages were firmly attached to her nose. \nTerrified, she exclaimed: "They\'ll be there for the rest of my life!"\n   Feeling sorry for his wife and wondering how he could ever put up with a \nwoman with such an awkward nose, the woodcutter said: "I\'ll try." Grasping the\nstring of sausages, he tugged with all his might. But he simply pulled his \nwife over on top of him. The pair sat on the floor, gazing sadly at each other.\n   "What shall we do now?" they said, each thinking the same thought.\n   "There\'s only one thing we can do . . ." ventured the woodcutter\'s wife \ntimidly.\n   "Yes, I\'m afraid so . . ." her husband sighed, remembering their dreams of \nriches, and he bravely wished the third and last wish "I wish the sausages \nwould leave my wife\'s nose."\n   And they did. Instantly, husband and wife hugged each other tearfully, \nsaying "Maybe we\'ll be poor, but we\'ll be happy again!"\n   That evening, the only reminder of the woodcutter\'s meeting with the elf \nwas the string of sausages. Some,\nhowever, have already gained publicity through the papers, and\nothers have not offered a field for those peculiar qualities which\nmy friend possessed in so high a degree, and which it is the\nobject of these papers to illustrate. Some, too, have baffled his\nanalytical skill, and would be, as narratives, beginnings without\nan ending, while others have been but partially cleared up, and\nhave their explanations founded rather upon conjecture and sur-\nmise than on that absolute logical proof which was so dear to\nhim. There is, however, one of these last which was so remark-\nable in its details and so startling in its results that I am tempted\nto give some account of it in spite of the fact that there are points\nin connection with it which never have been, and probably never\nwill be, entirely cleared up.\n  The year \'87 furnished us with a long series of cases of\ngreater or less interest, of which I retain the records. Among my\nheadings under this one twelve months I find an account of the\nadventure of the Paradol Chamber, of the Amateur Mendicant\nSociety, who held a luxurious club in the lower vault of a\nfurniture warehouse, of the facts connected with the loss of the\nBritish bark Sophy Anderson, of the singular adventures of the\nGrice Patersons in the island of Uffa, and finally of the Camberwell\npoisoning case. In the latter, as may be remembered, Sherlock\nHolmes was able, by winding up the dead man\'s watch, to prove\nthat it had been wound up two hours before, and that therefore\nthe deceased had gone to bed within that time -- a deduction\nwhich was of the greatest importance in clearing up the case. All\nthese I may sketch out at some future date, but none of them\npresent such singular features as the strange train of circum-\nstances which I have now taken up my pen to describe.\n  It was in the latter days of September, and the equinoctial\ngales had set in with exceptional violence. All day the wind had\nscreamed and the rain had beaten against the windows, so that\neven here in the heart of great, hand-made London we were\nforced to raise our minds for the instant from the routine of life\nand to recognize the presence of those great elemental forces\nwhich shriek at mankind through the bars of his civilization, like\nuntamed beasts in a cage. As evening drew in, the storm grew\nhigher and louder, and the wind cried and sobbed like a child in\nthe chimney. Sherlock Holmes sat moodily at one side of the\nfireplace cross-indexing his records of crime, while I at the other\nwas deep in one of Clark Russell\'s fine sea-stories until the howl\nof the gale from without seemed to blend with the text, and the\nsplash of the rain to lengthen out into the long swash of the sea\nwaves. My wife was on a visit to her mother\'s, and for a few\ndays I was a dweller once more in my old quarters at Baker\nStreet.\n  "Why," said I, glancing up at my companion, "that was\nsurely the bell. Who could come to-night? Some friend of yours,\nperhaps?"\n  "Except yourself I have none," he answered. "I do not\nencourage visitors."\n  "A client, then?"\n  "If so, it is a serious case. Nothing less would bring a man\nout on such a day and at such an hour. But I take it that it is\nmore likely to be some crony of the landlady\'s."\n  Sherlock Holmes was wrong in his conjecture, however, for\nthere came a step in the passage and a tapping at the door. He\nstretched out his long arm to turn the lamp away from himself\nand towards the vacant chair upon which a newcomer must sit.\n  "Come in!" said he.\n  The man who entered was young, some two-and-twenty at the\noutside, well-groomed and trimly clad, with something of refine-\nment and delicacy in his bearing. The streaming umbrella which\nhe held in his hand, and his long shining waterproof told of the\nfierce weather through which he had come. He looked about him\nanxiously in the glare of the lamp, and I could see that his face\nwas pale and his eyes heavy, like those of a man who is weighed\ndown with some great anxiety.\n  "l owe you an apology," he said, raising his golden pince-nez\nto his eyes. "I trust that I am not intruding. I fear that I have\nbrought some traces of the storm and rain into your snug chamber."\n  "Give me your coat and umbrella," said Holmes. "They may\nrest here on the hook and will be dry presently. You have come\nup from the south-west, I see."\n  "Yes, from Horsham."\n  "That clay and chalk mixture which I see upon your toe caps\nis quite distinctive."\n  "I have come for advice."\n  "That is easily got."\n  "And help."\n  "That is not always so easy."\n  "I have heard of you, Mr. Holmes. I heard from Major\nPrendergast how you saved him in the Tankerville Club scandal."\n  "Ah, of course. He was wrongfully accused of cheating at\ncards."\n  "He said that you could solve anything."\n  "He said too much."\n  "That you are never beaten."\n  "I have been beaten four times  -  three times by men, and\nonce by a woman."\n  "But what is that compared with the number of your successes?"\n  "It is true that I have been generally successful."\n  "Then you may be so with me."\n  "I beg that you will draw your chair up to the fire and favour\nme with some details as to your case."\n  "It is no ordinary one."\n  "None of those which come to me are. I am the last court of\nappeal."\n  "And yet I question, sir, whether, in all your experience, you\nhave ever listened to a more mysterious and inexplicable chain of\nevents than those which have happened in my own family."\n  "You fill me with interest," said Holmes. "Pray give us the\nessential facts from the commencement, and I can afterwards\nquestion you as to those details which seem to me to be most\nimportant."\n  The young man pulled his chair up and pushed his wet feet out\ntowards the blaze.\n  "My name," said he, "is John Openshaw, but my own affairs\nhave, as far as I can understand, little to do with this awful\nbusiness. It is a hereditary matter; so in order to give you an idea\nof the facts, I must go back to the commencement of the affair.\n  "You must know that my grandfather had two sons -- my\nuncle Elias and my father Joseph. My father had a small factory\nat Coventry, which he enlarged at the time of the invention of\nbicycling. He was a patentee of the Openshaw unbreakable tire,\nand his business met with such success that he was able to sell it\nand to retire upon a handsome competence.\n  "My uncle Elias emigrated to America when he was a young\nman and became a planter in Florida, where he was reported to\nhave done very well. At the time of the war he fought in\nJackson\'s army, and afterwards under Hood, where he rose to be\na colonel. When Lee laid down his arms my uncle returned to his\nplantation, where he remained for three or four years. About\n1869 or 1870 he came back to Europe and took a small estate in\nSussex, near Horsham. He had made a very considerable fortune\nin the States, and his reason for leaving them was his aversion to\nthe negroes, and his dislike of the Republican policy in extend-\ning the franchise to them. He was a singular man, fierce and\nquick-tempered, very foul-mouthed when he was angry, and of a\nmost retiring disposition. During all the years that he lived at\nHorsham, I doubt if ever he set foot in the town. He had a\ngarden and two or three fields round his house, and there he\nwould take his exercise, though very often for weeks on end he\nwould never leave his room. He drank a great deal of brandy and\nsmoked very heavily, but he would see no society and did not\nwant any friends, not even his own brother.\n  "He didn\'t mind me; in fact, he took a fancy to me, for at the\ntime when he saw me first I was a youngster of twelve or so.\nThis would be in the year 1878, after he had been eight or nine\nyears in England. He begged my father to let me live with him\nand he was very kind to me in his way. When he was sober he\nused to be fond of playing backgammon and draughts with me,\nand he would make me his representative both with the servants\nand with the tradespeople, so that by the time that I was sixteen I\nwas quite master of the house. I kept all the keys and could go\nwhere I liked and do what I liked, so long as I did not disturb\nhim in his privacy. There was one singular exception, however,\nfor he had a single room, a lumber-room up among the attics,\nwhich was invariably locked, and which he would never permit\neither me or anyone else to enter. With a boy\'s curiosity I have\npeeped through the keyhole, but I was never able to see more\nthan such a collection of old trunks and bundles as would be\nexpected in such a room.\n  "One day -- it was in March, 1883 -- a letter with a foreign\nstamp lay upon the table in front of the colonel\'s plate. It was\nnot a common thing for him to receive letters, for his bills were\nall paid in ready money, and he had no friends of any sort. \'From\nIndia!\' said he as he took it up, \'Pondicherry postmark! What\ncan this be?\' Opening it hurriedly, out there jumped five little\ndried orange pips, which pattered down upon his plate. I began\nto laugh at this, but the laugh was struck from my lips at the\nsight of his face. His lip had fallen, his eyes were protruding, his\nskin the colour of putty, and he glared at the envelope which he\nstill held in his trembling hand, \'K. K. K.!\' he shrieked, and\nthen, \'My God, my God, my sins have overtaken me!\'\n  " \'What is it, uncle?\' I cried.\n  " \'Death,\' said he, and rising from the table he retired to his\nroom, leaving me palpitating with horror. I took up the envelope\nand saw scrawled in red ink upon the inner flap, just above the\ngum, the letter K three times repeated. There was nothing else\nsave the five dried pips. What could be the reason of his over-\npowering terror? I left the breakfast-table, and as I ascended the\nstair I met him coming down with an old rusty key, which must\nhave belonged to the attic, in one hand, and a small brass box,\nlike a cashbox, in the other.\n  " \'They may do what they like, but I\'ll checkmate them still,\'\nsaid he with an oath. \'Tell Mary that I shall want a fire in my\nroom to-day, and send down to Fordham, the Horsham lawyer.\'\n  "I did as he ordered, and when the lawyer arrived I was asked\nto step up to the room. The fire was burning brightly, and in the\ngrate there was a mass of black, fluffy ashes, as of burned paper,\nwhile the brass box stood open and empty beside it. As I glanced\nat the box I noticed, with a start, that upon the lid was printed\nthe treble K which I had read in the morning upon the envelope.\n  " \'I wish you, John,\' said my uncle, \'to witness my will. I\nleave my estate, with all its advantages and all its disadvantages,\nto my brother, your father, whence it will, no doubt, descend to\nyou. If you can enjoy it in peace, well and good! If you find you\ncannot, take my advice, my boy, and leave it to your deadliest\nenemy. I am sorry to give you such a two-edged thing, but I\ncan\'t say what turn things are going to take. Kindly sign the\npaper where Mr. Fordham shows you.\'\n  "I signed the paper as directed, and the lawyer took it away\nwith him. The singular incident made, as you may think, the\ndeepest impression upon me, and I pondered over it and turned it\nevery way in my mind without being able to make anything of it.\nYet I could not shake off the vague feeling of dread which it left\nbehind, though the sensation grew less keen as the weeks passed\nand nothing happened to disturb the usual routine of our lives. I\ncould see a change in my uncle, however. He drank more than\never, and he was less inclined for any sort of society. Most of his\ntime he would spend in his room, with the door locked upon the\ninside, but sometimes he would emerge in a sort of drunken\nfrenzy and would burst out of the house and tear about the\ngarden with a revolver in his hand, screaming out that he was\nafraid of no man, and that he was not to be cooped up, like a\nsheep in a pen, by man or devil. When these hot fits were over\nhowever, he would rush tumultuously in at the door and lock and\nbar it behind him, like a man who can brazen it out no longer\nagainst the terror which lies at the roots of his soul. At such\ntimes I have seen his face, even on a cold day, glisten with\nmoisture, as though it were new raised from a basin.\n  "Well, to come to an end of the matter, Mr. Holmes, and not\nto abuse your patience, there came a night when he made one of\nthose drunken sallies from which he never came back. We found\nhim, when we went to search for him, face downward in a little\ngreen-scummed pool, which lay at the foot of the garden. There\nwas no sign of any violence, and the water was but two feet\ndeep, so that the jury, having regard to his known eccentricity,\nbrought in a verdict of \'suicide.\' But I, who knew how he\nwinced from the very thought of death, had much ado to persuade\nmyself that he had gone out of his way to meet it. The matter\npassed, however, and my father entered into possession of the\nestate, and of some 14,000 pounds, which lay to his credit at the\nbank."\n  "One moment," Holmes interposed, "your statement is, I\nforesee, one of the most remarkable to which I have ever lis-\ntened. Let me have the date of the reception by your uncle of the\nletter, and the date of his supposed suicide."\n  "The letter arrived on March 10, 1883. His death was seven\nweeks later, upon the night of May 2d."\n  "Thank you. Pray proceed."\n  "When my father took over the Horsham property, he, at my\nrequest, made a careful examination of the attic, which had been\nalways locked up. We found the brass box there, although its\ncontents had been destroyed. On the inside of the cover was a\npaper label, with the initials of K. K. K. repeated upon it, and\n\'Letters, memoranda, receipts, and a register\' written beneath.\nThese, we presume, indicated the nature of the papers which had\nbeen destroyed by Colonel Openshaw. For the rest, there was\nnothing of much importance in the attic save a great many\nscattered papers and note-books bearing upon my uncle\'s life in\nAmerica. Some of them were of the war time and showed that he\nhad done his duty well and had borne the repute of a brave\nsoldier. Others were of a date during the reconstruction of the\nSouthern states, and were mostly concerned with politics, for he\nhad evidently taken a strong part in opposing the carpet-bag\npoliticians who had been sent down from the North.\n  "Well, it was the beginning of \'84 when my father came to\nlive at Horsham, and all went as well as possible with us until\nthe January of \'85. On the fourth day after the new year I heard\nmy father give a sharp cry of surprise as we sat together at the\nbreakfast-table. There he was, sitting with a newly opened enve-\nlope in one hand and five dried orange pips in the outstretched\npalm of the other one. He had always laughed at what he called\nmy cock-and-bull story about the colonel, but he looked very\nscared and puzzled now that the same thing had come upon\nhimself.\n  " \'Why, what on earth does this mean, John?\' he stammered.\n  "My heart had turned to lead. \'It is K. K. K.,\' said I.\n  "He looked inside the envelope. \'So it is,\' he cried. \'Here are\nthe very letters. But what is this written above them?\'\n  " \'Put the papers on the sundial,\' I read, peeping over his\nshoulder.\n  " \'What papers? What sundial?\' he asked.\n  " \'The sundial in the garden. There is no other,\' said I; \'but\nthe papers must be those that are destroyed.\'\n  " \'Pooh!\' said he, gripping hard at his courage. \'We are in a\ncivilized land here, and we can\'t have tomfoolery of this kind.\nWhere does the thing come from?\'\n  " \'From Dundee,\' I answered, glancing at the postmark.\n  " \'Some preposterous practical joke,\' said he. \'What have I to\ndo with sundials and papers? I shall take no notice of such\nnonsense.\'\n  " \'I should certainly speak to the police,\' I said.\n  " \'And be laughed at for my pains. Nothing of the sort.\'\n  " \'Then let me do so?\'\n  " \'No, I forbid you. I won\'t have a fuss made about such\nnonsense.\'\n  "It was in vain to argue with him, for he was a very obstinate\nman. I went about, however, with a heart which was full of\nforebodings.\n  "On the third day after the coming of the letter my father went\nfrom home to visit an old friend of his, Major Freebody, who is\nin command of one of the forts upon Portsdown Hill. I was glad\nthat he should go, for it seemed to me that he was farther from\ndanger when he was away from home. In that, however, I was in\nerror. Upon the second day of his absence I received a telegram\nfrom the major, imploring me to come at once. My father had\nfallen over one of the deep chalk-pits which abound in the\nneighbourhood, and was lying senseless, with a shattered skull. I\nhurried to him, but he passed away without having ever recov-\nered his consciousness. He had, as it appears, been returning\nfrom Fareham in the twilight, and as the country was unknown\nto him, and the chalk-pit unfenced, the jury had no hesitation in\nbringing in a verdict of \'death from accidental causes.\' Carefully\nas I examined every fact connected with his death, I was unable\nto find anything which could suggest the idea of murder. There\nwere no signs of violence, no footmarks, no robbery, no record\nof strangers having been seen upon the roads. And yet I need not\ntell you that my mind was far from at ease, and that I was\nwell-nigh certain that some foul plot had been woven round him.\n  "In this sinister way I came into my inheritance. You will ask\nme why I did not dispose of it? I answer, because I was well\nconvinced that our troubles were in some way dependent upon an\nincident in my uncle\'s life, and that the danger would be as\npressing in one house as in another.\n  "It was in January, \'85, that my poor father met his end, and\ntwo years and eight months have elapsed since then. During that\ntime I have lived happily at Horsham, and I had begun to hope\nthat this curse had passed way from the family, and that it had\nended with the last generation. I had begun to take comfort too\nsoon, however; yesterday morning the blow fell in the very\nshape in which it had come upon my father."\n  The young man took from his waistcoat a crumpled envelope,\nand turning to the table he shook out upon it five little dried\norange pips.\n  "This is the envelope," he continued. "The postmark is\nLondon -- eastern division. Within are the very words which\nwere upon my father\'s last message: \'K. K. K.\'; and then \'Put\nthe papers on the sundial.\' "\n  "What have you done?\'\' asked Holmes.\n  "Nothing."\n  "Nothing?"\n  "To tell the truth" -- he sank his face into his thin, white\nhands -- "I have felt helpless. I have felt like one of those poor\nrabbits when the snake is writhing towards it. I seem to be in the\ngrasp of some resistless, inexorable evil, which no foresight and\nno precautions can guard against."\n  "Tut! tut!" cried Sherlock Holmes. "You must act, man, or\nyou are lost. Nothing but energy can save you. This is no time\nfor despair."\n  "I have seen the police."\n  "Ah!"\n  "But they listened to my story with a smile. I am convinced\nthat the inspector has formed the opinion that the letters are all\npractical jokes, and that the deaths of my relations were really\naccidents, as the jury stated, and were not to be connected with\nthe warnings."\n  Holmes shook his clenched hands in the air. "Incredible\nimbecility!" he cried.\n  "They have, however, allowed me a policeman, who may re-\nmain in the house with me."\n  "Has he come with you to-night?"\n  "No. His orders were to stay in the house."\n  Again Holmes raved in the air.\n  "Why did you come to me," he cried, "and, above all, why\ndid you not come at once?"\n  "I did not know. It was only to-day that I spoke to Major\nPrendergast about my troubles and was advised by him to come\nto you."\n  "It is really two days since you had the letter. We should have\nacted before this. You have no further evidence, I suppose, than\nthat which you have placed before us -- no suggestive detail\nwhich might help us?"\n  "There is one thing," said John Openshaw. He rummaged in\nhis coat pocket, and, drawing out a piece of discoloured, blue-\ntinted paper, he laid it out upon the table. "I have some remem-\nbrance," said he, "that on the day when my uncle burned the\npapers I observed that the small, unburned margins which lay\namid the ashes were of this particular colour. I found this single\nsheet upon the floor of his room, and I am inclined to think that\nit may be one of the papers which has, perhaps, fluttered out\nfrom among the others, and in that way has escaped destruction.\nBeyond the mention of pips, I do not see that it helps us much. I\nthink myself that it is a page from some private diary. The\nwriting is undoubtedly my uncle\'s."\n  Holmes moved the lamp, and we both bent over the sheet of\npaper, which showed by its ragged edge that it had indeed been\ntorn from a book. It was headed, "March, 1869," and beneath\nwere the following enigmatical notices:\n\n     4th. Hudson came. Same old platform.\n\n     7th. Set the pips on McCauley, Paramore, and John Swain,\n          of St. Augustine.\n     9th. McCauley cleared.\n     1Oth. John Swain cleared.\n     12th. Visited Paramore. All well.\n\n  "Thank you!" said Holmes, folding up the paper and return-\ning it to our visitor. "And now you must on no account lose\nanother instant. We cannot spare time even to discuss what you\nhave told me. You must get home instantly and act."\n  "What shall I do?"\n  "There is but one thing to do. It must be done at once. You\nmust put this piece of paper which you have shown us into the\nbrass box which you have described. You must also put in a note\nto say that all the other papers were burned by your uncle, and\nthat this is the only one which remains. You must assert that in\nsuch words as will carry conviction with them. Having done\nthis, you must at once put the box out upon the sundial, as\ndirected. Do you understand?"\n  "Entirely."\n  "Do not think of revenge, or anything of the sort, at present. I\nthink that we may gain that by means of the law; but we have\nour web to weave, while theirs is already woven. The first\nconsideration is to remove the pressing danger which threatens\nyou. The second is to clear up the mystery and to punish the\nguilty parties."\n  "I thank you," said the young man, rising and pulling on his\novercoat. "You have given me fresh life and hope. I shall\ncertainly do as you advise."\n  "Do not lose an instant. And, above all, take care of yourself\nin the meanwhile, for I do not think that there can be a doubt that\nyou are threatened by a very real and imminent danger. How do\nyou go back?\n  "By train from Waterloo."\n  "It is not yet nine. The streets will be crowded, so l trust that\nyou may be in safety. And yet you cannot guard yourself too\nclosely."\n  "I am armed."\n  "That is well. To-morrow I shall set to work upon your case."\n  "I shall see you at Horsham, then?"\n  "No, your secret lies in London. It is there that I shall seek\nit."\n  "Then I shall call upon you in a day, or in two days, with\nnews as to the box and the papers. I shall take your advice in\nevery particular." He shook hands with us and took his leave.\nOutside the wind still screamed and the rain splashed and pat-\ntered against the windows. This strange, wild story seemed to\nhave come to us from amid the mad elements -- blown in upon us\nlike a sheet of sea-weed in a gale -- and now to have been\nreabsorbed by them once more.\n  Sherlock Holmes sat for some time in silence, with his head\nsunk forward and his eyes bent upon the red glow of the fire.\nThen he lit his pipe, and leaning back in his chair he watched the\nblue smoke-rings as they chased each other up to the ceiling.\n  "I think, Watson," he remarked at last, "that of all our cases\nwe have had none more fantastic than this."\n  "Save, perhaps, the Sign of Four."\n  "Well, yes. Save, perhaps, that. And yet this John Openshaw\nseems to me to be walking amid even greater perils than did the\nSholtos."\n  "But have you," I asked, "formed any definite conception as\nto what these perils are?"\n  "There can be no question as to their nature," he answered.\n  "Then what are they? Who is this K. K. K., and why does he\npursue this unhappy family?"\n  Sherlock Holmes closed his eyes and placed his elbows upon\nthe arms of his chair, with his finger-tips together. "The ideal\nreasoner," he remarked, "would, when he had once been shown\na single fact in all its bearings, deduce from it not only all the\nchain of events which led up to it but also all the results which\nwould follow from it. As Cuvier could correctly describe a\nwhole animal by the contemplation of a single bone, so the\nobserver who has thoroughly understood one link in a series of\nincidents should be able to accurately state all the other ones,\nboth before and after. We have not yet grasped the results which\nthe reason alone can attain to. Problems may be solved in the\nstudy which have baffled all those who have sought a solution by\nthe aid of their senses. To carry the art, however, to its highest\npitch, it is necessary that the reasoner should be able to utilize all\nthe facts which have come to his knowledge; and this in itself\nimplies, as you will readily see, a possession of all knowledge,\nwhich, even in these days of free education and encyclopaedias,\nis a somewhat rare accomplishment. It is not so impossible,\nhowever, that a man should possess all knowledge which is\nlikely to be useful to him in his work, and this I have endeav-\noured in my case to do. If I remember rightly, you on one\noccasion, in the early days of our friendship, defined my limits\nin a very precise fashion."\n  "Yes," I answered, laughing. "It was a singular document.\nPhilosophy, astronomy, and politics were marked at zero, I\nremember. Botany variable, geology profound as regards the\nmud-stains from any region within fifty miles of town, chemistry\neccentric, anatomy unsystematic, sensational literature and crime\nrecords unique, violin-player, boxer, swordsman, lawyer, and\nself-poisoner by cocaine and tobacco. Those, I think, were the\nmain points of my analysis."\n  Holmes grinned at the last item. "Well," he said, "I say\nnow, as I said then, that a man should keep his little brain-attic\nstocked with all the furniture that he is likely to use, and the rest\nhe can put away in the lumber-room of his library, where he can\nget it if he wants it. Now, for such a case as the one which has\nbeen submitted to us to-night, we need certainly to muster all our\nresources. Kindly hand me down the letter K of the American\nEncyclopaedia which stands upon the shelf beside you. Thank\nyou. Now let us consider the situation and see what may be\ndeduced from it. In the first place, we may start with a strong\npresumption that Colonel Openshaw had some very strong rea-\nson for leaving America.
